rk of spiritual knowledge. \n=C2=A0 \nAghora series is ni=\r\nce, but can give wrong notions to some who may tend to be fascinated by ext=\r\nernal miracles. I have no doubt that Vimalananda had no confusions himself,=\r\n but some people reading those books can form misconceptions (though it is =\r\nstill ok if that makes them do sadhana. The only problem is if they start d=\r\noing the bad karma of making negative judgments on greats thinking they are=\r\n blindly following Vimalananda). It is a good idea to balance the perspecti=\r\nve with some Vedantic understanding such as Yoga Vasishtham or Bhagavad Git=\r\na. \n=C2=A0 \n&gt; Infact it also violates a point which you yourself made in an=\r\n earlier mail. The \n&gt; external is connected to the internal. Some siddhis a=\r\nre not possible unless one \n&gt; attains a very rarified level of realization.=\r\n And they manifest externally. \n=C2=A0 \nYes, some external siddhis are poss=\r\nible only at a very rarefied level of realization. But some with the same o=\r\nr higher level of realization may not possess the same external siddhi. Thu=\r\ns external miracles cannot be used as measures of one&#39;s level. \n=C2=A0 \nThi=\r\ns is like the analogy I gave of collecting fruits from the trees on the sid=\r\ne of the road to the hilltop. Some keep tavelling on the road and accept on=\r\nly those fruits that land in their lap by themselves. Some get distracted f=\r\nrom the journey and pursue the fruits actively. Collecting fruits is neithe=\r\nr necessary nor sufficient for reaching the top. Though having a fruit that=\r\n is available only at a very high altitude shows that one has reached great=\r\n altitude, it cannot be used as a measure of one&#39;s progress, for someone ma=\r\ny have climbed greater heights without collecting that (or any) fruit. \n=C2=\r\n=A0 \nExternal and internal do NOT have a one-to-one correspondence. Just as=\r\n you cannot tell what is inside a house by looking at it from outside, so c=\r\nannot you tell one&#39;s state of mind from looking at one. One&#39;s spiritual mat=\r\nurity and attainment is in one&#39;s state of mind. \n=C2=A0 \n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 * \n=\r\n=C2=A0 \n&gt; If a loved and revered spiritual figure is percieved to be questi=\r\noned, \n&gt; naturally a reaction is expected. I am not surprised. \n=C2=A0 \nWhe=\r\nn you said a while back, for example, that Vivekananda used to contradict h=\r\nimself, I agreed. The issue is not just &quot;questioning&quot; a &quot;loved and revered =\r\nspiritual figure&quot;. The issue is passing off what I see as needless, unjusti=\r\nfied and baseless judgments, driven by misconceptions and a fascination for=\r\n the external. \n=C2=A0 \nBest regards, \nNarasimha \n-------------------------=\r\n------------------------------------------ \n=C2=A0 Free Jyotish Software, F=\r\nree Jyotish Lessons, Jyotish Writings, \n&quot;Do It Yourself&quot; ritual manuals for=\r\n short Homam and Pitri Tarpana: \n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 http://www.Ved=\r\nicAstrologer.org \n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 Films that make a difference: ht=\r\ntp://SaraswatiFilms.org \n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 Spirituality: http://grou=\r\nps.yahoo.com/group/vedic-wisdom \n=C2=A0 Jyotish writings: http://groups.yah=\r\noo.com/group/JyotishWritings \n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n Twitter ID: @homam108 \n---------------------------------------------------=\r\n---------------- \n=C2=A0 \n=C2=A0 \nOn Wed, Aug 3, 2011 at 4:22 AM, rajarshi =\r\nnandy wrote: \n=C2=A0 =C2=A0 \nDear Narasimha, \n=C2=A0 \nHopefully, this will =\r\nbe my last mail on this topic, since I see that I am merely reiterating mys=\r\nelf. I have nothing new to add. \n=C2=A0 \n&lt;&lt; Do you believe that you can