stand Vimalananda&#39;s order (Paramahamsa \n&gt; &lt; Siddha &lt; Natha &lt; Rishi),=\r\n please note that different hierarchies exist \n&gt; in scriptures for deities =\r\nalso. Some consider a hierarchy of deities \n&gt; where Vishnu is supreme. Some=\r\n consider a hierarchy of deities where \n&gt; Shiva is supreme. Some consider a=\r\n hierarchy of deities where Shakti is \n&gt; supreme. And so on. None of them i=\r\ns absolute. All of them are relative \n&gt; and for specific purposes, i.e. fro=\r\nm a specific perspective. There are \n&gt; people who take them as absolute and=\r\n argue that so and so thing taught \n&gt; by Vishnu is superior to so and so th=\r\ning taught by Shiva, etc. But we \n&gt; know that none of the hierarchies is ab=\r\nsolute. \n&gt; \n&gt; One who has the nerve to think that one can compare the wisdo=\r\nm of \n&gt; Jnaneshwar, dispassion of Ramana Maharshi, mad devotion of Ramakris=\r\nhna \n&gt; Paramahamsa, detached activism of Vivekananda, compassion of Shirdi =\r\nSai, \n&gt; spiritual ecstasy of Vama Khepa, inner clarity of Lahiri Mahashaya,=\r\n \n&gt; detachment of Trilinga Swami, purity of Tukaram, humility of Eknath \n&gt; =\r\nMaharaj, ecstatic love of Meera Bai, motherly love of Gopaler Ma, etc, \n&gt; i=\r\ns a fool of the highest order. They can be compared from specific \n&gt; limite=\r\nd perspectives. In one thing, Tukaram may be superior to all, in \n&gt; another=\r\n Jnaneshwar, in another Trilinga, in another Ramakrishna, and so \n&gt; on. You=\r\n cannot compare in absolute terms. You should not even try to. \n&gt; You shoul=\r\nd just appreciate them individually and aspire to be like any \n&gt; of them th=\r\nat you like the most. \n&gt; \n&gt; Vimalananda&#39;s list may be correct from specific=\r\n perspective. More \n&gt; importantly, his words should make one realize that t=\r\nhere is always \n&gt; scope for further self-control (and the resulting mastery=\r\n over the field \n&gt; of duality) while one i